2. Base Test mein Logger Setup karna
Aapko hamesha Logger ko Base Class mein initialize karna chahiye taaki har test class use use kar sake.

Java

import org.apache.logging.log4j.LogManager;
import org.apache.logging.log4j.Logger;

public class BaseTest {
    public static WebDriver driver;
    // Logger initialize karna
    public static Logger log = LogManager.getLogger(BaseTest.class.getName());

    @BeforeMethod
    public void setup() {
        log.info("- Test Case Execution Started -"); //need to use 3 dashes instead of 1
        driver = new ChromeDriver();
        log.info("Chrome Browser Launched");
        
        driver.get("https://example.com");
        log.info("Navigated to URL");
    }
}
3. Test Case mein Logs likhna
Jab aap BaseTest ko extend karte hain, toh aap log object ko kahin bhi use kar sakte hain:

Java

public class LoginTest extends BaseTest {

    @Test
    public void testLogin() {
        log.info("Starting login test...");
        
        driver.findElement(By.id("user")).sendKeys("admin");
        log.debug("Entered username"); // Debug level for detailed info
        
        driver.findElement(By.id("pass")).sendKeys("123");
        log.debug("Entered password");
        
        if(driver.getTitle().equals("Home")) {
            log.info("Login Successful!");
        } else {
            log.error("Login Failed! Title mismatch.");
        }
    }
}
4. Log Levels (Kaunsa kab use karein?)
Ek hybrid framework mein levels ka sahi use zaroori hai:

Level	Kab use karein?
INFO	General steps ke liye (e.g., "Browser Started", "Test Finished").
DEBUG	Choti details ke liye (e.g., "Typing 'Admin' in textbox").
ERROR	Jab koi assertion fail ho ya element na mile.
FATAL	Jab test execution hi ruk jaye (e.g., DB connection failed).
WARN	Jab kuch unexpected ho lekin test chalta rahe.

